## 8. Deep-Dive Edge Cases & Failure Modes
Capturing these edge cases now protects the application's architecture from breaking when it encounters messy real-world corporate data.

| Edge Case | The Engineering Risk | The App Solution / Guardrail |
|---|---|---|
| The Mid-Year Rubric Change | Corporate goals or team structures change halfway through the year, making old logs irrelevant to the new categories. | Implement Temporal Versioning on the evaluation_rubrics table. Logs retain their original vector embeddings but can be dynamically re-mapped to the new rubric versions at runtime. |
| The Redaction Hallucination | The local AI engine accidentally over-redacts common engineering words (e.g., masking standard frameworks like "Spring Security" as proprietary code). | Maintain a strict, localized Whitelisting Dictionary of industry-standard tech terms, libraries, and protocols that the PII/SPI sanitizer cannot modify. |
| Manager-Peer Cross-Contamination | A manager uses the app to track feedback for their team, risking an employee's private personal reflections leaking into the manager's ledger. | Enforce absolute database isolation via Row-Level Security (RLS) in Postgres. Peer feedback logs authored by a manager exist in an entirely separate schema namespace from an employee’s self-tracked journal logs. |
| The Ghost Multiplier (Hidden Criteria) | HR text uses non-standard scoring scales (e.g., evaluating performance based on an "Alpha-Scale" A/B/C rather than numerical 1–5 rankings). | Build a Normalized Score Translator into the JSON schema, mapping any custom company scale back to a universal 5-tier internal standard (Low, Developing, Proficient, Advanced, Exceptional). |

